computeInvariants

public TemporalInvariantSet computeInvariants(IGraph<LogEvent> g,
                                              boolean filterTautological)
Compute invariants of a graph g by mining invariants from the transitive closure using extractInvariantsUsingTC, which returns an over-approximation of the invariants that hold (i.e. it may return invariants that do not hold, but may not fail to return an invariant that does not hold)

Parameters:
g - the graph of nodes of type LogEvent
filterTautological - whether or not tautological invariants should be filtered out
Returns:
the set of temporal invariants the graph satisfies

filterOutTautologicalInvariants

private void filterOutTautologicalInvariants(java.util.Set<ITemporalInvariant> invariants)
The inclusion of INITIAL and TERMINAL states in the graphs generates the following types of invariants (for all event types X): 
 - x AP TERMINAL
 - INITIAL AP x
 - x AP TERMINAL
 - x AFby TERMINAL
 - TERMINAL NFby INITIAL

NOTE: x AP TERMINAL is not considered a tautological invariant, but we filter it out anyway because we reconstruct it later.

We filter these out by simply ignoring any temporal invariants of the form x INV y where x or y in {INITIAL, TERMINAL}. This filtering is useful because it relieves us from checking invariants which are true for all graphs produced with typical construction.

Note that this filtering, however, could filter out more invariants then the ones above. We rely on unit tests to make sure that the two sets are equivalent. 
 TODO: Final graphs should always satisfy all these invariants.
       Convert this observation into an extra sanity check.

computeINITIALAFbyXInvariants

private java.util.Set<ITemporalInvariant> computeINITIALAFbyXInvariants(IGraph<LogEvent> g)
Computes the 'INITIAL AFby x' invariants = 'eventually x' invariants. We do this by considering the set of events in one partition, and then removing the events from this set when we do not find them in other partitions.
